{{Use Pakistani English|date=November 2017}}
'''Progressive Education Network''' is a [[non-profit organization]] that seeks to improve [[Education in Pakistan|public education]] in [[Pakistan]] by ''adopting'' schools and by entering into partnerships with companies that pledge to assist schools in their area. Its main focus is on [[primary school]]s. The company was started by seven professional friends and adopted its first schools in [[Lahore]] in 2010. Its chief executive officer is Omar Khayyam Sheikh.<ref name=Today/>
== History == Progressive Education Network was founded by a group of seven friends, professionals, businessmen, and educators, who wanted to improve public education in Pakistan as a means of assisting people from the lower end of society. They decided to adopt existing schools rather than building their own, and studied models such as [[BRAC (NGO)|BRAC]], [[Citizens Foundation]] and [[CARE (relief agency)|CARE]].<ref name=Today>{{cite news |url=http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2014/01/25/national/pen-seeking-to-provide-quality-education-to-a-million-children-by-2025/ |title=PEN: Seeking to provide quality education to a million children by 2025 |newspaper=Pakistan Today |date=January 25, 2014 |type=interview|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Arif Butt |author2=Shezeen Hemani |url=https://hbr.org/product/progressive-education-network-pen-creating-social-impact-in-pakistan/NA0204-PDF-ENG |title=Case Study: Progressive Education Network (PEN): Creating Social Impact in Pakistan |journal=Harvard Business Review |date=October 1, 2012|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> They incorporated the company as a non-profit with the [[Securities and Exchange Commission of Pakistan]] under Section 42 of the Companies Ordinance 1984; it has been certified by the Pakistan Centre for Philanthropy as adhering to best practices for non-profits.<ref name=Today/>
In 2010 the company adopted its first schools, in Lahore, with a total of more than 6,000 students. Initially the founders and their friends funded it themselves; subsequently they developed sponsorship relationships with for-profit companies, including a Good Neighbor Program through which a company sponsors assistance to schools in its locality. They have declared a goal of improving the education of 1&nbsp;million children throughout Pakistan by 2025.<ref name=Today/> By January 2014, it had expanded to schools totaling almost 11,000 students in a number of locations in Pakistan, including [[Karachi]], [[Gujrat City|Gujrat]] and [[Muzaffargarh]].<ref name=Today/> {{As of|2016|07}}, it had adopted 89 schools with almost 23,500 students and had signed an agreement to adopt 50 schools in [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1135083/non-profit-take-charge-50-public-schools/ |title=Non-profit to take charge of 50 public schools |newspaper=The Express Tribune |date=July 3, 2016|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>
== Methods == Progressive Education Network adopts state schools through a public-private partnership; it is one of several groups using this method to improve education in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Rabea Malik |author2=Faisal Bari |author3=et al |url=http://ideaspak.org/images/Publications/Human-Development/Public-Private-Partnerships-Education-Report.pdf |title=Partnerships for Management in Education: Evidence from Punjab and Sindh |publisher=Institute of Development and Economic Alternatives |date=August 2015 |type=research report }}</ref> It works to improve them by improving their infrastructure, for example toilet facilities, drinking water, and classroom furniture, and monitoring teachers, hiring additional teachers to reduce class sizes, and providing teacher training during the summer and winter holidays. The company also provides staff to clean schools twice a day, organizes debate, quiz, and sporting contests, and has provided computers and funded computer classes, but it places its highest priority on hiring more teachers and improving their training.<ref name=Today/>
